<subSubSection pageId="242" pageNumber="521" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="242.[781,1374,1402,1825]" pageId="242" pageNumber="521">
Records referred to G. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[1105,1193,1635,1668]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Graomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edithae">edithae</taxonomicName>
from Chumbicha in Catamarca Province belong to G. 
<taxonomicName box="[821,972,1714,1747]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="griseoflavus">griseoflavus</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="242" pageNumber="521" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6708158" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6708158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6708158/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" targetBox="[166,757,1405,1819]" targetPageId="242">
<paragraph blockId="242.[781,1374,1402,1825]" pageId="242" pageNumber="521">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[781,956,1753,1786]" pageId="242" pageNumber="521">Distribution.</emphasis>
Restricted to the type locality in S top of Ambato Range, NW 
<taxonomicName box="[1222,1366,1796,1825]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Argentina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Argentina</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="242" pageNumber="521" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="242.[166,1375,1839,2652]" pageId="242" pageNumber="521">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,422,1839,1864]" pageId="242" pageNumber="521">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 108 mm, tail 127 mm, ear 20 mm, hindfoot 25 mm (from holotype). No specific data are available for body weight. The Otro Cerro Pericote 1s the smallest species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1916" box="[624,733,1910,1943]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Graomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Graomys</taxonomicName>
. Dorsal color is similar to that of the Common Pericote (G. 
<taxonomicName box="[432,583,1949,1982]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="griseoflavus">griseoflavus</taxonomicName>
) but without buffy wash on sides of latter. Underparts are white, as on the Chaco Pericote (
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. A. Allen" authorityYear="1901" box="[694,872,1989,2022]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Phyllotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chacoensis">G. chacoensis</taxonomicName>
), lacking slaty base characteristic of the Pale Pericote (G. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[469,588,2028,2061]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Graomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="242" pageNumber="521" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domorum">domorum</taxonomicName>
) and some populations of the Common Pericote. Tail is absolutely and proportionately shorter than that of the Common Pericote,less heavily haired terminally but bicolored, brown above and white below. Skull is a miniature of congeners but notable for absence of beading on supraorbital edges.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
